Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: My motivation stems from the persistent challenge in self-supervised monocular depth estimation: the degradation of normal and depth accuracy in textureless regions such as walls, roads, or uniformly colored surfaces. Traditional methods rely heavily on photometric consistency, which fails when pixel intensities lack variation. While SQLdepth introduces a self-cost volume to model relative geometry and PPEA-Depth enables efficient adaptation to dynamic scenes, neither explicitly addresses uncertainty-driven refinement in geometrically ambiguous areas. The idea of spherical coordinate perturbation—nudging surface normals in angular space rather than Cartesian depth—offers a more natural way to explore plausible orientations in low-texture zones. By combining this with pixelwise depth intervals (i.e., depth bounds per pixel inferred from context), we can constrain and refine estimates where gradients vanish. Inspired by the non-linear structural probe’s use of kernelized transformations to reveal hidden structure, I propose an uncertainty-guided active probing mechanism that dynamically selects regions for perturbation based on confidence, effectively "probing" the environment through synthetic spherical noise to elicit informative responses in otherwise silent regions. This differs from prior work by introducing *active*, *uncertainty-aware* geometric exploration during training, not just passive inference. It integrates geometric reasoning (via spherical coordinates) with statistical confidence (via depth intervals) in a self-supervised loop, enabling the network to learn how to interrogate its own uncertainties—a meta-cognitive strategy for depth refinement.

